emarkable achievements paradoxically grew out of the deep differences—in language, class, education, and location—that began to divide native society in the 1960s. Drawing on fifteen years of fieldwork, Rudi Colloredo-Mansfeld explores these differences and the conflicts they engendered in a variety of communities. From protestors confronting the military during a national strike to a migrant family fighting to get a relative released from prison, Colloredo-Mansfeld recounts dramatic events and private struggles alike to demonstrate how indigenous power in Ecuador is energized by disagreements over values and priorities, eloquently contending that the plurality of Andean communities, not their unity, has been the key to their political success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunity developmentxEcuador. 0aCommunity organizationxEcuador. 0aIndian activistsxEcuador. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxPolitics and government. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxSocial conditions. 0aPolitical activistsxEcuador. 0aPolitical participationxEcuador. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acommunity, resistance, revolution, activism, politics, andes, ecuador, indigenous, land rights, development, environmentalism, conservation, politicians, elections, representative government, representation, constitution, multiculturalism, diversity, race, ethnicity, language, class, education, geography, south america, nonfiction, history, sociology, gender, political science, anthropology, fieldwork, ethnography, difference, strike, labor, protest, immigration, migrant workers, prison, legal system, plurality, indians, organization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z9783110635386